cf6ae58a38252a90f6a82ab4c4e428df.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1d3ac094b2d7bbfcde957e29edd82643f5af8414.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/ac1fcbbde3f168e7c9a4b04e6257bae03b244e40.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a36cc08cb8dc02e6e284f095c1f95743972262f3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b926981a641fad976e34946edee0af2e88975cbb.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/69ea4fb360541ea40af2742c758877e23debcca3.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/6/6bb0bbdece043dc2c316430250ca47d8daa634f2.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/3/3f5d4f08762604fa3c3745d482e8c9807e7421c2.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/16e3e22d02a05b3670859abdf1a9c7736a7b270b.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b2d0a49a8a9ee972b02390416efa3cb03cbf48a.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8c0ed1122a306c6cd839a1f2e2933eba47208527.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/c/c76d68482d1655fac9c03eb8891877d9f1f1523e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/f00c124851c7e9fe0014844d33dd01548f82200e.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":".\n\n\n  \n   Configure Filter(s) \n In the Filter Set Filter details, select your  Entity  and  Filter , and the  Name  will be created automatically. For example: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/d9ba70b166b1fbe69462add8865955eecc64ba2f.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for managing a data schema item titled \u0022Task_TasksAfterDeadline.\u0022 The top section shows a filter titled \u0022Task_TasksAfterDeadline,\u0022 with several attributes listed under (Info) such as \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable\u0022 (set to False), and \u0022Name\u0022 (set to \u0022Task_TasksAfterDeadline\u0022). Under the Condition section, the attributes include \u0022IgnoreFilterConstant,\u0022 \u0022IgnoreFilterParameterName,\u0022 and \u0022PassWhenParameterMatch\u0022 (also set to False). In the Misc section, the \u0022Entity\u0022 is labeled as \u0022Task,\u0022 and the filter is identified as \u0022TasksAfterDeadline.\u0022 The purpose appears to be configuring and managing filter conditions for a task data entry system.\n\n\n  \n Save it, and your Filter Set will be ready to use. \n   Lookup settings \n When defining a Filter Set in Lookup Data Structures, you need to configure them in the Lookup details using the  ListMethod  property. If the Filter Set is properly configured in the Lookup Data Structure, you can select it here. For example: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/d/db5e9926cf6ae58a38252a90f6a82ab4c4e428df.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for a Data Service Lookup configuration titled \u0022Task_Name_GetId.\u0022 It includes various sections such as Info, Filter, List, and Misc, with corresponding fields and parameters. The Info section details the schema item attributes like \u0022Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Inheritable,\u0022 and \u0022Name.\u0022 In the List section, the \u0022ListMethod\u0022 is prominently highlighted, indicating a method called \u0022GetByDueDate.\u0022 Other fields like \u0022ListSortSet,\u0022 \u0022ListValueMember,\u0022 and \u0022SearchByFirstColumnOnly\u0022 are also present, showcasing the setup for querying and organizing tasks based on due dates within the data service context. The overall purpose appears to be the configuration of a data retrieval method related to task management.\n\n\n  \n Save it, and now your Lookup will display only items based on your Filter Set settings. \n   Identifying the right Data Structure \n In some cases, you may not be sure which Data Structure you need to create a Filter Set for. To choose the right Data Structure, follow these steps: \n   Open the Screen \n In the Model Browser, go to  User Interface  /  Screens , under the package folder of your application, double-click on the Screen name where the drop-down menu you want to work with is located. \n   Select the Screen Section \n In the Screen editor, select the Screen Section where the drop-down menu you want to edit is located. If there is only one Screen Section in your Screen, the entire block may look like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/1/1d3ac094b2d7bbfcde957e29edd82643f5af8414.png]\nDescription: The interface presented is a screen titled \u0022Task\u0022 within a software environment, likely for managing tasks or workflow processes. The left panel contains a section labeled \u0022Data Source\u0022 with fields for \u0022Name,\u0022 \u0022Id,\u0022 and \u0022Package,\u0022 displaying values such as \u0022Task,\u0022 \u0022787f829-80d1-48d2-bd8c-4add425700,\u0022 and \u0022taskmanager\u0022 respectively. Below, a \u0022Toolbox\u0022 displays various options including \u0022BusinessPartner_CreateMe,\u0022 \u0022BusinessPartner_NewUser,\u0022 \u0022BusinessPartnerOrigramRole,\u0022 and others. The main working area includes a section titled \u0022Task\u0022 with input fields that seem to be placeholders, as indicated by ellipses (\u2026). Navigation buttons are also visible, featuring options for adding, deleting, or navigating through entries. The overall purpose appears to be the configuration or management of task-related data within the application.\n\n\n  \n   View the Properties \n Then, in the right bar of the Architect, switch to the  Properties  tab: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/ac1fcbbde3f168e7c9a4b04e6257bae03b244e40.png]\nDescription: The image displays the ORIGAM Architect interface, specifically the \u0022Task\u0022 screen within the \u0022myapplication\u0022 model. ","vector_